@DurpVonFronz Atmospheric electricity is a real thing, and a good search term to aquant yourself with the basic consepts. But because the ions in the air are so few, and air is such a good insulator.  There is very very little current from sky to ground, with lightning being the obvious exception. We can pretty much ignore anecdotal acounts ball lightning sightings for this discussion, because It's not observed or reproduced by scientist. 

And from the ground up, yes it iss about 100v potential per meter, but because the amount of current is sooooooo very vrry tiny, it's is and always will be a lab curiosity. I'd hardly call it technology, in that technology is usually used to refer to useful ideas represented in man made things that are useful rather than useless ideas. But i am satisfied with knowledge, or knowledge of atmospheric electricity. 

Maybe maybe knowledge of atmospheric electricity might inspire to make your plants grow, proving your own electricity and call it electroculture or electric horticulture, or plant electrotropisim. Maybe then you'll have some usefull technology.  But powering your cellphone computer or airconditioner you will not.
